column9: P1. Leave the policy settings as they are.
column10: P2. Political measures that focus on less regulation  (e.g., policies that promote free trade agreements by reducing food regulations)
column11: P3. Political measures that include moderate regulation toward sustainable food production (e.g., banning certain pesticides, providing incentives for organic farming).
column12: P4. Political measures that include radical regulation toward sustainable food production (e.g., banning all pesticides, banning the import of foods produced using unsustainable methods).
column13: P5. Political measures that create incentives for local producers to produce sustainable foods (e.g., subsidies or tax breaks for local farmers who produce organic products).
column14: P6. Political measures aimed at investing in research to develop sustainable agricultural techniques or materials.
